        "content": "<p>The antipode of a Hopf algebra is almost the same as the inverse of a group object. </p>\n<p>I am wondering if a group object in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msubsup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">g</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">k</mi><mtext>op</mtext></msubsup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\"> \\mathsf{Alg}_{\\mathbb{k}}^{\\text{op}}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0797em;vertical-align:-0.2974em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">Alg</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7823em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4026em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathbb mtight\">k</span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.1809em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord text mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\">op</span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2974em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> is precisely a Hopf algebra over <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{k}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">k</span></span></span></span>, where the comultiplication, counit, and antipode are given by the (opposites of) group multiplication, group unit, and the inverse, respectively. </p>\n<p>[For clarity, I am defining the category <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">g</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">k</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Alg}_{\\mathbb{k}}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9386em;vertical-align:-0.2441em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">Alg</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2381em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4559em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathbb mtight\">k</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2441em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> to be the category of (unital) rings sliced under <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{k}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">k</span></span></span></span>, I am taking for granted that the 2 definitions of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{k}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">k</span></span></span></span>-algebra (one as a monoid in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{k}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">k</span></span></span></span>-vector spaces, another as a ring that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{k}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">k</span></span></span></span> maps into) coincide.]</p>\n<p>I think all the diagrams that are supposed to commute translates between these, but the types of arrows don't quite check out. For example, the (opposite of) the inverse map is a map of <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{k}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">k</span></span></span></span>-algebras, but the antipode of a Hopf algebra is only required to be <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{k}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">k</span></span></span></span>-linear.</p>",
        "id": 515550621,
        "sender_full_name": "Jack Jia",
        "timestamp": 1746121549
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm not sure about the antipode, but a different point is that you do need to be talking about <em>commutative</em> rings in order that the tensor product in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">g</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">k</mi></msub></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Alg}_{\\Bbbk}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.9386em;vertical-align:-0.2441em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">Alg</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2381em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4559em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathbb mtight\">k</span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2441em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span> coincides with the cartesian product in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><msubsup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">A</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"sans-serif\">g</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">k</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">o</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">p</mi></mrow></msubsup></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathsf{Alg}_{\\Bbbk}^{\\mathrm{op}}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:1.0797em;vertical-align:-0.2974em;\"></span><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord\"><span class=\"mord mathsf\" style=\"margin-right:0.01389em;\">Alg</span></span><span class=\"msupsub\"><span class=\"vlist-t vlist-t2\"><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.7823em;\"><span style=\"top:-2.4026em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathbb mtight\">k</span></span></span></span><span style=\"top:-3.1809em;margin-right:0.05em;\"><span class=\"pstrut\" style=\"height:2.7em;\"></span><span class=\"sizing reset-size6 size3 mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mtight\"><span class=\"mord mathrm mtight\">op</span></span></span></span></span></span><span class=\"vlist-s\">​</span></span><span class=\"vlist-r\"><span class=\"vlist\" style=\"height:0.2974em;\"><span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span></span>.  But maybe you're one of the people for whom all rings are commutative?  (-:</p>",
        "id": 515560058,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1746125004
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>That restriction does also mean that you only end up with commutative Hopf algebras this way.  (I guess the non-commutative ones are \"quantum groups\".)</p>",
        "id": 515560268,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1746125079
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"276777\">@Mike Shulman</span> </p>\n<p>I think if all rings are commutative, those are already the affine group schemes and there's no real point in calling them Hopf algebras! Also thanks for pointing out the products don't really coincide!</p>",
        "id": 515563689,
        "sender_full_name": "Jack Jia",
        "timestamp": 1746126381
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"428716\">@Jean-Baptiste Vienney</span> </p>\n<p>I think maybe I didn't explain well: I meant that <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{k}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">k</span></span></span></span>-algebras are monoids (not quite, because you will be taking <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{k}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">k</span></span></span></span> in the position of the terminal object in <span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"double-struck\">k</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mathbb{k}</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.6889em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathbb\">k</span></span></span></span>-vector spaces), not Hopf algebras.</p>",
        "id": 515564134,
        "sender_full_name": "Jack Jia",
        "timestamp": 1746126579
    },
    {
