    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"738970\">Jack Jia</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/411257-theory.3A-mathematics/topic/Can.20we.20define.20a.20Hopf.20algebra.20as.20a.20group.20object.3F/near/515563689\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I think if all rings are commutative, those are already the affine group schemes and there's no real point in calling them Hopf algebras!</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Well, if there's a difference between \"commutative ring\" and \"affine scheme\", there should be the same difference between \"commutative Hopf algebra\" and \"affine group scheme\", right?</p>",
        "id": 515565257,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1746127027
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>(That is, they are the objects of a pair of contravariantly-equivalent categories.)</p>",
        "id": 515565301,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1746127046
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"276777\">Mike Shulman</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/411257-theory.3A-mathematics/topic/Can.20we.20define.20a.20Hopf.20algebra.20as.20a.20group.20object.3F/near/515565257\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"738970\">Jack Jia</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/411257-theory.3A-mathematics/topic/Can.20we.20define.20a.20Hopf.20algebra.20as.20a.20group.20object.3F/near/515563689\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I think if all rings are commutative, those are already the affine group schemes and there's no real point in calling them Hopf algebras!</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Well, if there's a difference between \"commutative ring\" and \"affine scheme\", there should be the same difference between \"commutative Hopf algebra\" and \"affine group scheme\", right?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>Sorry, I am a bit confused - In this case, won't \"commutative Hopf algebra\" and \"affine group scheme\" both be on the \"affine scheme\" side?</p>",
        "id": 515565847,
        "sender_full_name": "Jack Jia",
        "timestamp": 1746127212
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>On the off-chance you aren't already aware of this: the book \"Monoidal Functors, Species and Hopf Algebras\" talks about Hopf monoids internal to a braided monoidal category. I believe the <a href=\"https://ncatlab.org/nlab/show/Hopf+monoid\">nLab</a> says that one can recover Hopf algebras as a special case.</p>",
        "id": 515570334,
        "sender_full_name": "David Egolf",
        "timestamp": 1746128937
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"738970\">Jack Jia</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/411257-theory.3A-mathematics/topic/Can.20we.20define.20a.20Hopf.20algebra.20as.20a.20group.20object.3F/near/515565847\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>won't \"commutative Hopf algebra\" and \"affine group scheme\" both be on the \"affine scheme\" side?</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p>I don't think so  -- why would they be?</p>",
        "id": 515570381,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1746128958
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>A homomorphism of commutative Hopf algebras is in particular a homomorphism of underlying commutative rings, which goes in the opposite direction from the map of affine (group) schemes.</p>",
        "id": 515570460,
        "sender_full_name": "Mike Shulman",
        "timestamp": 1746128994
    }
]